Thereâ€™s a reason we capture video. It isnâ€™t just to document; itâ€™s to take a moment, what you see, and hold it forever. A moment in time, frozen. But more and more, thatâ€™s how we interpret life itself.

Itâ€™s why itâ€™s so much harder to be topical. The way we communicate is less and less bound to the present. Unconsciously we post to Instagram with the understanding that that is our â€œimageâ€ or persona. It is the best of our pictures. It is the resume of online presence.

Streaming. YouTube. Instagram. Twitter. The Internet Archive. The moment something exists digitally, it is accessible at any time. It isnâ€™t just about technologyâ€”books, magazines, journals, any article of thought made physical have always functioned this way.

Video and online media make it self-evident. A book doesnâ€™t remind you that it is an artifact of time; a YouTuber literally says, â€œWhenever you watch thisâ€¦â€ It is aware of itself as something created then but experienced whenever. Even if no one ever watches it again, the moment it holds still exists.

This is why podcasting is a paradox. No medium is both as ephemeral and as eternal as podcasting. Episodes are recorded daily, responding to the immediate nowâ€”news, trends, thoughtsâ€”but they persist for years. Long, sprawling conversations, meant to be engaged in real-time, but accessible whenever. They are artifacts of the present, meant for the future. They create a strange kind of time loop. Recorded with the knowledge of its specific moment, yet consumed out of time by individuals scattered across future eras. It is a ripple of the past caught for the future.

As technology advancesâ€”AI, the Metaverse, whatever comes nextâ€”the gap between the immediate and the permanent blurs even further. People feel it, even if they donâ€™t name it. Does it ever seem like things donâ€™t matter unless theyâ€™re recorded? That what trends on TikTok, what racks up views on YouTube, does it matter more? Why do likes and comments hold weight? Are they a kind of gravity? Confirmation that your moment in time was consequential. When a video reaches 78 trillion views or whatever will be the most, ever escalating, how much gravity does that moment hold?

Does truth bend toward engagement?

Or is it more necessary than ever to allow the mind to remain fluid? Because as AI advances, fabricating truth becomes easier. A picture used to be proof. Now, does a picture prove anything? AI, Photoshop, deepfakes. reality can be undone and remade in an instant. 

If the moment is no longer real, and the record is no longer proof, then what is left to trust?

Yourself. Trust your mind to handle uncertainty. To engage and debunk. Skepticism is only wrong if it impedes correct action.

But if truth bends toward engagement, does that mean reality itself is becoming performative? If the things that gain the most traction shape perception, does that mean the most visible truth becomes the dominant truth, regardless of whether it reflects reality? If people live through their records, curating themselves for the future instead of existing fully in the present, then does real-time experience still hold the same weight? Or does the knowledge that every moment is archived strip it of its authenticity?

If record no longer equals proof, does that mean history itself is no longer fixed? If anything can be recreated, rewritten, or reimagined in the future, is it possible that the concept of an objective past is dissolving? If deepfakes and AI-generated memories become indistinguishable from reality, will people remember things that never happened? Will they forget things that did? And if history can be altered, is there any truth left that exists outside of perception?

Maybe the only answer is to cultivate a mind that is strong enough to resist being defined by what is seen. If reality can be manipulated, then the ability to hold contradictions and engage with uncertainty becomes the only real skill that matters. Ludus Veritatis is one small way. But if the nature of truth itself is changing, is there any approach that can truly keep up? Or is the only move left to let go of certainty altogether and learn to navigate the illusion?

